{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BNsk7iv83yKJ9tBAwT8u8c","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Since protoc is not available, I have two options:\n1. Manually edit the generated proto files (fragile, complex)\n2. Skip the gRPC layer and implement the feature purely at the server level with a non-protobuf approach\n\nActually, the cleanest approach would be to:\n1. Add the domain/loop changes (TaskSnapshot)\n2. Add a direct method to the gRPC server (not as a gRPC RPC, but as a direct method that the web handler and CLI can call)\n3. For the CLI, use the web API instead of gRPC (like `logs --follow` already does)\n\n\n4. For the web, add the API endpoint directly\n\nThe CLI needs to talk to the daemon, and while most commands use gRPC, `logs --follow` already demonstrates using HTTP/SSE directly. I could follow that same pattern with a `tasks` command that calls the HTTP API endpoint. Manually editing the generated protobuf code is too error-prone, so the better approach is to add `ListTasks` to the proto file for documentation purposes, but implement the actual feature through the web API endpoint that the CLI will call via HTTP.\n\nLet me think through the implementation: I need to add task snapshot tracking to the loop, expose that state through a web handler at `/api/projects/{name}/tasks`, and then have the CLI `tasks` command call that endpoint. But I'm realizing the web handler might not have direct access to the gRPC server's loop map, so I need to check how the daemon wires these components together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1087,"cache_read_input_tokens":84503,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1087},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6146b7bf-a511